On August 12, 2017, a car was deliberately driven into a crowd of people who were peacefully protesting the Unite the Right rally in Charlottesville, Virginia. The incident killed one person and injured 20 more. The driver of the car, 20-year-old ames Alex Fields Jr., had previously claimed neo-Nazi and white supremacist beliefs. On March 20, 2019, he pled guilty to 29 federal charges and was sentenced to life in prison. The Mayor of Charlottesville, the Attorney General, and the FBI all called the attack an act of domestic terrorism.

More than a thousand people attended the memorial service held for the woman killed in the attack, 32-year-old Heather Heyer.Hundreds of people gathered at vigils in Virginia and in many other U.S. Cities, such as Philadelphia and Columbus. 

The news spread on social media, with hundreds of thousands of people sending wishes and prayers to the people of Charlottesville in the immediate few days following the attack. This is an example of how news coverage and social media spread awareness about a dangerous act of domestic terrorism. 